questionContent.body:
Read the argument carefully and choose the best option to strengthen, weaken, or resolve the situation presented. Each question is constructed to challenge

logical reasoning and evaluation of abstract scenarios.


A multinational firm invested in an AI recruitment platform that analyses

candidate tone, word choice, and body language in virtual interviews. HR

personnel later observed that high-potential candidates were being overlooked

disproportionately.


Which of the following, if true, most plausibly explains the issue?


A. The AI system was trained on limited data sets, leading to cultural and linguistic bias.


B. The company’s job listings were not adequately promoted across platforms.


C. Several candidates opted for audio-only interviews due to bandwidth issues.


D. Traditional interviews were still conducted for executive-level positions.

solution.name: Solution 1
solution.details: Hint: Bias in AI training data can skew evaluation criteria, affecting candidate selection unfairly.

questionContent.body:
A university implemented mandatory climate literacy modules across disciplines,

claiming it would produce environmentally responsible graduates. A post-course

survey, however, revealed only marginal improvement in sustainable behaviour.


Which ofthe following best explains this gap?


A. The module emphasized theoretical frameworks but lacked application-based learning.


B. Students expressed strong pre-existing interest in sustainability before enrolling.


C. The program received widespread acclaim in academic circles.


D. The module was developed in collaboration with international environmental

agencies.

solution.name: Solution 1
solution.details: Hint: A lack of applied focus explains why awareness did not translate into changed behaviour.

questionContent.body:
Read the argument carefully and choose the best option to strengthen, weaken, or resolve the situation presented. Each question is constructed to challenge

logical reasoning and evaluation of abstract scenarios.

A pharmaceutical company introduced a non-addictive painkiller that showed effectiveness in clinical trials. However, patient adherence to the medication regimen remained low post-launch.


Which of the following best accounts for this discrepancy?


A. Patients found the dosage schedule of the new drug more demanding than conventional treatments.


B. Regulatory approvals delayed the product's entry into certain international

markets.


C. The medication’s branding was perceived as generic and lacked appeal.


D. Doctors reported fewer side effects with the new painkiller compared to

opioid-based drugs.

solution.name: Solution 1
solution.details: Hint: Complex dosage discourages patient adherence, explaining the gap between trial efficacy and real-world usage.

questionContent.body:
Read the argument carefully and choose the best option to strengthen, weaken, or resolve the situation presented. Each question is constructed to challenge

logical reasoning and evaluation of abstract scenarios.                                               

A leading education journal argued that incorporating virtual laboratories in science education enhances experiential learning. Yet, in a longitudinal study,

students exposed to virtual labs scored similarly on conceptual assessments as those taught using traditional demonstrations.


Which of the following, if true, most weakens the journal's claim?


A. The virtual labs lacked interactivity and real-time feedback compared to physical labs.


B. Teachers were equally qualified in both the experimental and control groups.


C. Students in both groups had access to supplemental reading material.


D. The study was conducted in a single school district with limited technological infrastructure.

solution.name: Solution 1
solution.details: Hint: Lack of interactivity in virtual labs undercuts their supposed experiential benefit.

questionContent.body:
Read the argument carefully and choose the best option to strengthen, weaken, or resolve the situation presented. Each question is constructed to challenge logical reasoning and evaluation of abstract scenarios. A city’s transportation department implemented dynamic congestion pricing in an effort to reduce peak-hour traffic. Although the initiative was projected to decrease congestion by 20%, traffic volume remained largely unchanged in the six months following its launch.


Which of the following, if true, best explains this outcome?


A. A majority of drivers were unaware of the

dynamic pricing structure and continued their routines.


B. The number of public buses and metro trains was increased significantly

during peak hours.


C. Similar congestion pricing models have shown varying success in other

metropolitan areas.


D. Most businesses in the central district began remote work policies shortly

after implementation.

solution.name: Solution 1
solution.details:
Hint: If drivers were unaware of

pricing changes, their behaviour wouldn't shift—explaining the unchanged

traffic.

questionContent.body:
Q travels towards East. M travels towards North. S and T travel in opposite directions. T travels towards right of Q. Which of the following is definitely

true?

questionOptions.body: M and S travel in the opposite directions.
M and S travel in the same direction.

solution.name: Solution 1
solution.details: We have been given that Q travels towards East and M travels towards North. Now, T travels towards right of Q implies that T travels towards South. Hence, S travels towards North (because S and T Travel in opposite directions). Therefore, it is definitely true that M and S travel in the same direction i.e., North.

In a certain code language “EASY” is written as “5117”. In the same code language, how will “BEAM” be written as?

solution.name: Solution 1
solution.details:
EASY → E

is the 5th alphabet in the series


A is the

first alphabet in the series


S is the

19th alphabet, which makes it (1+9 = 10 ⇒

1+0 = 1)

Y is the

25th alphabet, which makes it (2+5 = 7)


Hence,

EASY = 5117


Similarly,


BEAM → B

is the 2nd alphabet in the series


E is the

5th alphabet in the series


A is the

1st alphabet in the series


M is the

13th alphabet, which makes it (1+3 = 4)


Hence

BEAM = 2514
